{{Cleanup FJC Bio}}
'''Herbert Peter Sorg''' (December 19, 1911 &ndash; March 11, 1979) was a [[United States federal judge]].

Sorg was born in [[St. Mary's, Pennsylvania]]. He received a [[LL.B.]] from [[Duquesne University School of Law]] in 1935. He was in private practice of law in [[St. Mary's, Pennsylvania]] from 1935 to 1955. He was a Member, Pennsylvania House of Representatives from 1940 to 1953. He was a Majority whip from 1945 to 1947. He was a Majority leader in 1947. He was a Speaker from 1947 to 1953. 

Sorg was a federal judge to the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Pennsylvania]]. Sorg was nominated by President [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] on May 20, 1955, to a new seat created by 68 Stat. 8; He was confirmed by the [[United States Senate]] on July 29, 1955, and received commission on August 1, 1955. Served as chief judge, 1975-1976. Assumed [[senior status]] on December 20, 1976. Sorg<!-- -->'s service was terminated on March 11, 1979, due to death.

